- ...what was Emilio doing then?
- Nothing.

747
01:34:58,890 --> 01:35:01,850
He stopped flapping, didn't he?

748
01:35:04,190 --> 01:35:05,980
She told me later...

749
01:35:06,780 --> 01:35:09,150
...that the second she lifted up her foot

750
01:35:09,240 --> 01:35:13,450
and saw Emilio not flapping,
she knew what she had done.

751
01:35:13,530 --> 01:35:18,580
Is that not the perfect
visual image of life and death?

752
01:35:18,660 --> 01:35:24,000
A fish flapping on the carpet,
and a fish notflapping on the carpet.

753
01:35:26,000 --> 01:35:31,720
So powerful, even a four-year-old
with no concept of life or death...

754
01:35:31,800 --> 01:35:33,590
...knew what it meant.

755
01:35:34,840 --> 01:35:38,470
- You loved Emilio, didn't you?
- Uh-huh.

756
01:35:38,560 --> 01:35:41,480
Well... I love Mommy too.

757
01:35:43,020 --> 01:35:45,310
But I did to Mommy
what you did to Emilio.

758
01:35:45,400 --> 01:35:49,230
- You stomped on Mommy?
- Worse.

759
01:35:49,320 --> 01:35:51,360
I shot Mommy.

760
01:35:51,440 --> 01:35:54,610
Not pretend shooting
like we were just doing.

761
01:35:54,700 --> 01:35:56,490
I shot her for real.

762
01:35:56,570 --> 01:35:59,040
Why? Did you want to see
what would happen?

763
01:35:59,120 --> 01:36:03,670
No, I knew what would happen
to Mommy if I shot her.

764
01:36:03,750 --> 01:36:08,380
What I didn't know was, when I shot
Mommy, what would happen to me.

765
01:36:08,460 --> 01:36:12,300
- What happened?
- I was very sad.

766
01:36:14,380 --> 01:36:16,550
And that's when I learned...

767
01:36:16,640 --> 01:36:21,930
...some things, once you do,
they can never be undone.

768
01:36:24,940 --> 01:36:30,110
- What happened to Mommy?
- Why don't you ask Mommy?

769
01:36:30,190 --> 01:36:33,320
You OK, Mommy?
Does it hurt?

770
01:36:33,400 --> 01:36:35,320
No, sweetie.

771
01:36:37,200 --> 01:36:39,200
Doesn't hurt anymore.

772
01:36:45,290 --> 01:36:47,540
Did it make you sick?

773
01:36:48,210 --> 01:36:52,710
No. It made me sleep.

774
01:36:52,800 --> 01:36:55,880
That's why I haven't been with you. B.B.
I've been asleep.

775
01:36:55,970 --> 01:36:58,800
But you're awake now, Mommy. Right?

776
01:36:59,470 --> 01:37:02,770
I'm wide awake, pretty girl.

777
01:37:02,850 --> 01:37:08,100
B.B., would you like Mommy to watch
a video with you before sleepy time?

778
01:37:08,190 --> 01:37:09,560
Uh-huh.

779
01:37:09,650 --> 01:37:13,150
Mommy, do you want to watch
a video with me before sleepy time?

780
01:37:13,230 --> 01:37:16,240
Oh, yeah!
I would love to.

781
01:37:16,320 --> 01:37:19,030
<i>- Which one do you wanna watch?
- Shogun Assassin.</i>

782
01:37:19,120 --> 01:37:21,530
No, B.B.
Shogun Assassin is too long.

783
01:37:21,620 --> 01:37:25,710
- Mnh-mnh.
- No, it's not.

784
01:37:25,790 --> 01:37:30,500
Well, then, I'll leave you ladies to it.

785
01:37:37,010 --> 01:37:42,470
<i>When I was little,
my father was famous.</i>

786
01:37:42,560 --> 01:37:46,770
<i>He was the greatest samurai
in the empire.</i>

787
01:37:46,850 --> 01:37:50,150
<i>And he was the shogun's decapitator.</i>

788
01:37:50,230 --> 01:37:55,280
<i>He cut off the heads of 131 lords.</i>

789
01:37:55,360 --> 01:37:59,950
<i>My father would come home to Mother
and when he would see her,</i>

790
01:38:00,030 --> 01:38:02,780
<i>he would forget about the killings.</i>

791
01:38:02,870 --> 01:38:07,960
<i>He wasn't scared of the shogun,
but the shogun was scared of him.</i>

792
01:38:08,040 --> 01:38:10,710
<i>Maybe that was the problem.</i>

793
01:38:10,790 --> 01:38:13,670
<i>One night, the shogun sent...</i>

794
01:40:35,390 --> 01:40:38,310
I was just admiring your sword.

795
01:40:39,400 --> 01:40:41,320
Quite a piece of work.

796
01:40:42,650 --> 01:40:46,660
Speaking of which, how is Hanzo-san?

797
01:40:46,740 --> 01:40:48,200
He's good.

798
01:40:50,200 --> 01:40:52,200
Has his sushi gotten any better?

799
01:40:56,000 --> 01:41:01,090
You know, I couldn't believe it.
You got him to make you a sword.

800
01:41:01,170 --> 01:41:05,510
It was easy.
I just dropped your name, Bill.

801
01:41:05,590 --> 01:41:07,680
That'd do it.

802
01:41:38,880 --> 01:41:44,210
I suppose the idea is we cross
Hanzo swords. Am I right?

803
01:41:46,260 --> 01:41:47,840
Well,

804
01:41:47,930 --> 01:41:53,010
it just so happens this hacienda
has its own private beach.

805
01:41:53,100 --> 01:41:57,440
And that private beach just so happens
to look particularly beautiful

806
01:41:57,520 --> 01:41:59,190
bathed in moonlight.

807
01:42:00,520 --> 01:42:03,440
And there just so happens to be
a full moon out tonight.

808
01:42:03,520 --> 01:42:10,110
So, swordfighter, if you want
a swordfight, that's where I suggest.

809
01:42:10,200 --> 01:42:14,370
But if you wanna be old school about it...

810
01:42:14,450 --> 01:42:18,120
...and you know
I'm all about old school...

811
01:42:18,210 --> 01:42:21,880
...then we could wait until dawn
and slice each other up at sunrise

812
01:42:21,960 --> 01:42:24,130
like a couple of real-life honest...

813
01:42:26,340 --> 01:42:31,590
Now, if you don't settle down, I'm gonna
have to put one in your kneecap.

814
01:42:31,680 --> 01:42:34,930
And I hear tell that's
a very painful place to get shot in.

815
01:42:37,020 --> 01:42:41,480
I'm just fuckin' with you.

816
01:42:42,480 --> 01:42:43,940
Now...

817
01:42:44,690 --> 01:42:47,280
...when it comes to you...

818
01:42:47,360 --> 01:42:49,030
...and us...

819
01:42:50,990 --> 01:42:54,160
...I have a few unanswered questions.

820
01:42:54,240 --> 01:42:59,790
So, before this tale of bloody revenge
reaches its climax,

821
01:43:00,790 --> 01:43:05,380
I'm gonna ask you some questions,
and I want you to tell me the truth.

822
01:43:06,130 --> 01:43:09,130
However, therein lies a dilemma.

823
01:43:10,380 --> 01:43:12,970
Because when it comes
to the subject of me,

824
01:43:13,050 --> 01:43:18,270
I believe you are truly and utterly
incapable of telling the truth.

825
01:43:18,350 --> 01:43:22,900
Especially to me.
And least of all, to yourself.

826
01:43:22,980 --> 01:43:26,320
And when it comes to the subject of me,

827
01:43:26,400 --> 01:43:33,110
I am truly and utterly incapable
of believing anything you say.

828
01:43:33,200 --> 01:43:35,410
How do you suppose
we solve this dilemma?

829
01:43:35,490 --> 01:43:37,030
Well,

830
01:43:37,120 --> 01:43:39,330
it just so happens,

831
01:43:39,410 --> 01:43:41,460
I have a solution.

832
01:43:41,540 --> 01:43:44,000
- Aah!
- Gotcha!

833
01:43:44,080 --> 01:43:46,290
<i>Goddamn!</i>

834
01:43:48,750 --> 01:43:52,170
What the fuck
did you just shoot me with?

835
01:43:52,260 --> 01:43:56,010
My greatest invention.
Or at least my favorite.

836
01:43:56,680 --> 01:44:00,640
Don't touch it, or I'll stick another one
right in your cheek.

837
01:44:04,350 --> 01:44:10,610
What lies within that dart, just begging
to course its way through your veins...

838
01:44:10,690 --> 01:44:15,160
...is an incredibly potent
and quite infallible truth serum.

839
01:44:15,240 --> 01:44:18,240
I call it "The Undisputed Truth."

840
01:44:18,330 --> 01:44:22,870
Twice as strong as sodium pentothal,
with no druggie aftereffects.

841
01:44:23,910 --> 01:44:29,800
Except for a slight wave of euphoria.
You feel it?

842
01:44:29,880 --> 01:44:32,420
- Euphoria?
- Yeah.

843
01:44:32,510 --> 01:44:35,890
- No.
- Too bad.

844
01:44:37,010 --> 01:44:39,180
As you know...

845
01:44:39,260 --> 01:44:42,890
...I'm quite keen on comic books.

846
01:44:43,560 --> 01:44:46,480
Especially the ones about superheroes.

847
01:44:46,560 --> 01:44:52,190
I find the whole mythology
surrounding superheroes fascinating.

848
01:44:52,280 --> 01:44:55,910
Take my favorite superhero, Superman.

849
01:44:56,950 --> 01:45:00,030
Not a great comic book.
Not particularly well drawn.

850
01:45:01,620 --> 01:45:02,620
Mmm.

851
01:45:03,410 --> 01:45:05,790
But the mythology...

852
01:45:05,870 --> 01:45:09,290
The mythology is not only great,
it's unique.

853
01:45:09,960 --> 01:45:13,590
How long does this shit take
to go into effect?

854
01:45:13,670 --> 01:45:17,550
About two minutes. Just long enough
for me to finish my point.

855
01:45:17,640 --> 01:45:22,850
Now, a staple of the superhero
mythology is,

856
01:45:22,930 --> 01:45:25,890
there's the superhero
and there's the alter ego.

857
01:45:25,980 --> 01:45:30,270
Batman is actually Bruce Wayne,
Spider-Man is actually Peter Parker.

858
01:45:31,320 --> 01:45:35,280
When that character wakes up
in the morning, he's Peter Parker.

859
01:45:35,360 --> 01:45:39,870
He has to put on a costume
to become Spider-Man.

860
01:45:40,530 --> 01:45:46,410
And it is in that characteristic
Superman stands alone.

861
01:45:46,500 --> 01:45:49,290
Superman didn't become Superman.

862
01:45:49,380 --> 01:45:51,960
Superman was born Superman.

863
01:45:52,040 --> 01:45:55,550
When Superman wakes up
in the morning, he's Superman.

864
01:45:56,550 --> 01:45:59,140
His alter ego is Clark Kent.

865
01:46:00,010 --> 01:46:03,140
His outfit with the big red "S" -

866
01:46:03,220 --> 01:46:06,930
that's the blanket he was wrapped in
as a baby when the Kents found him.

867
01:46:07,020 --> 01:46:09,440
<i>Those are his clothes.</i>

868
01:46:09,980 --> 01:46:15,230
What Kent wears - the glasses,
the business suit - that's the costume.

869
01:46:15,320 --> 01:46:19,820
That's the costume Superman wears
to blend in with us.

870
01:46:21,490 --> 01:46:24,990
Clark Kent is how Superman views us.

871
01:46:25,080 --> 01:46:28,250
And what are the characteristics
of Clark Kent?

872
01:46:28,330 --> 01:46:29,870
He's weak...

873
01:46:30,830 --> 01:46:33,630
...he's unsure of himself...

874
01:46:33,710 --> 01:46:35,500
...he's a coward.

875
01:46:36,510 --> 01:46:41,590
Clark Kent is Superman's critique
on the whole human race.

876
01:46:43,350 --> 01:46:48,020
Sort of like Beatrix Kiddo
and Mrs. Tommy Plimpton.

877
01:46:49,060 --> 01:46:51,270
<i>Aso.</i>

878
01:46:51,350 --> 01:46:53,690
The point emerges.

879
01:46:55,360 --> 01:46:58,860
You would've worn the costume
of Arlene Plimpton.

880
01:46:58,940 --> 01:47:01,820
But you were born Beatrix Kiddo.

881
01:47:02,820 --> 01:47:07,950
And every morning when you woke up,
you'd still be Beatrix Kiddo.

882
01:47:08,040 --> 01:47:10,040
Oh, you can... take the needle out.

883
01:47:17,300 --> 01:47:19,630
Are you calling me a superhero?

884
01:47:19,720 --> 01:47:21,220
I'm calling you a killer.

885
01:47:21,880 --> 01:47:24,800
A natural born killer.

886
01:47:24,890 --> 01:47:28,560
You always have been,
and you always will be.

887
01:47:28,640 --> 01:47:30,770
Moving to El Paso...

888
01:47:30,850 --> 01:47:34,230
...working in a used record store...

889
01:47:34,310 --> 01:47:36,980
...goin' to the movies with Tommy...

890
01:47:37,070 --> 01:47:38,530
...clipping coupons.

891
01:47:38,610 --> 01:47:40,440
That's you...

892
01:47:40,530 --> 01:47:43,950
...trying to disguise yourself
as a worker bee.

893
01:47:44,030 --> 01:47:47,080
That's you tryin' to blend in with the hive.

894
01:47:47,160 --> 01:47:49,290
But you're not a worker bee.

895
01:47:50,540 --> 01:47:53,250
You're a renegade killer bee.

896
01:47:53,330 --> 01:47:56,460
And no matter how much beer you drank
or barbecue you ate

897
01:47:56,540 --> 01:47:59,590
or how fat your ass got,

898
01:47:59,670 --> 01:48:03,590
nothing in the world
would ever change that.

899
01:48:05,970 --> 01:48:07,760
First question:

900
01:48:10,140 --> 01:48:14,810
Did you really think your life in El Paso
was gonna work?

901
01:48:21,240 --> 01:48:22,950
No!

902
01:48:26,490 --> 01:48:29,540
But I would've had B.B.!

903
01:48:29,620 --> 01:48:32,200
Don't get me wrong.

904
01:48:32,290 --> 01:48:36,210
I think you would have been
a wonderful mother.

905
01:48:36,290 --> 01:48:38,380
But you are a killer.

906
01:48:42,970 --> 01:48:45,630
All those people you killed to get to me...

907
01:48:45,720 --> 01:48:48,300
...felt damn good, didn't they?

908
01:48:50,390 --> 01:48:52,060
Yes.

909
01:48:52,980 --> 01:48:55,390
Every single one of them?

910
01:49:05,490 --> 01:49:07,320
Yes.

911
01:49:10,660 --> 01:49:13,200
That was the warmup round.

912
01:49:13,290 --> 01:49:17,960
Now comes the $64,000 question.

913
01:49:25,300 --> 01:49:29,010
Why did you run away
from me with my baby?

914
01:49:32,850 --> 01:49:36,270
Do you remember the last assignment
you sent me on?

915
01:49:36,350 --> 01:49:38,060
Of course.

916
01:49:38,810 --> 01:49:40,860
Lisa Wong.

917
01:49:42,110 --> 01:49:44,900
The morning I left, I was sick.

918
01:49:46,450 --> 01:49:49,530
On the plane, I threw up.

919
01:49:50,870 --> 01:49:53,370
So I started thinking:

920
01:49:54,790 --> 01:49:57,000
Maybe I was pregnant.

921
01:49:57,080 --> 01:50:02,420
"Easy to use. Remove cap and urinate
on the absorbent end for five seconds.

922
01:50:03,710 --> 01:50:06,220
"Accurate results in only 90 seconds.

923
01:50:06,300 --> 01:50:09,760
You can read the results as soon as
the line appears in the window."

924
01:50:46,000 --> 01:50:47,010
Fuck.

925
01:50:47,090 --> 01:50:49,300
<i>What I didn't know...</i>

926
01:50:49,380 --> 01:50:53,510
<i>...was that somewhere on my journey
I had been spotted.</i>

927
01:50:53,600 --> 01:50:59,770
<i>With me in L.A., it didn't take Lisa Wong
long to send an assassin of her own.</i>

928
01:51:00,940 --> 01:51:02,440
Hello, can I help you?

929
01:51:02,520 --> 01:51:05,980
Hello, I'm Karen Kim.
I'm the hospitality manager of the hotel.

930
01:51:06,070 --> 01:51:08,070
I have a welcome gift
from the management.

931
01:51:08,150 --> 01:51:09,400
Oh, that's nice. Um...

932
01:51:10,780 --> 01:51:12,450
Can you just leave it by the door?

933
01:51:24,960 --> 01:51:28,840
- You pretty good with that shotgun?
- Not that I have to be at this range,

934
01:51:28,920 --> 01:51:30,800
but I'm a fuckin' surgeon
with this shotgun.

935
01:51:30,880 --> 01:51:33,930
Well, guess what, bitch?
I'm better than Annie Oakley.

936
01:51:34,010 --> 01:51:37,390
- And I got you right in my sight.
- I could blow your fuckin' head off.

937
01:51:37,470 --> 01:51:41,640
Not before I put one
right between your eyes, so let's talk.

938
01:51:43,350 --> 01:51:45,150
Karen...

939
01:51:47,360 --> 01:51:49,780
...I just found out...

940
01:51:49,860 --> 01:51:51,700
...right now...

941
01:51:51,780 --> 01:51:56,030
...not a moment before
you blew a hole through the door...

942
01:51:57,830 --> 01:52:02,080
- ...that I'm pregnant.
- What is this?

943
01:52:02,160 --> 01:52:04,540
On the floor by the door...

944
01:52:04,630 --> 01:52:08,300
...is a strip that says I'm pregnant.

945
01:52:08,380 --> 01:52:09,550
Bullshit.

946
01:52:10,670 --> 01:52:14,220
Any other time
you'd be 100 percent right.

947
01:52:14,300 --> 01:52:16,140
This time...

948
01:52:17,720 --> 01:52:19,520
...you're 100 percent wrong.

949
01:52:21,560 --> 01:52:24,480
I'm the deadliest woman in the world.

950
01:52:25,480 --> 01:52:27,610
But right now...

951
01:52:27,690 --> 01:52:30,360
...I'm just scared shitless for my baby.

952
01:52:31,150 --> 01:52:32,820
Please.

953
01:52:34,360 --> 01:52:36,740
Just look at the strip.

954
01:52:38,740 --> 01:52:40,540
Please.

955
01:52:41,830 --> 01:52:46,540
Stay where you are and don't move.

956
01:53:03,730 --> 01:53:05,690
I don't know what this fuckin' shit means.

957
01:53:05,770 --> 01:53:07,730
The box with the directions -
it's right there.

958
01:53:20,240 --> 01:53:22,040
"Easy to use.

959
01:53:22,120 --> 01:53:26,670
Remove the cap and urinate
on the absorbent end."

960
01:53:26,750 --> 01:53:28,380
Blue means pregnant.

961
01:53:28,460 --> 01:53:31,210
I'll read it myself, thank you.

962
01:53:39,010 --> 01:53:40,720
Oh, OK.

963
01:53:40,800 --> 01:53:42,680
Say I were to believe you.
What then?

964
01:53:42,760 --> 01:53:44,810
Just go home.

965
01:53:47,100 --> 01:53:49,270
I'll do the same.

966
01:54:08,790 --> 01:54:10,460
Congratulations.

967
01:54:14,050 --> 01:54:16,840
<i>Before that strip turned blue...</i>

968
01:54:16,920 --> 01:54:19,380
...I was a woman, I was your woman.

969
01:54:20,390 --> 01:54:23,640
I was a killer who killed for you.

970
01:54:23,720 --> 01:54:27,180
Before that strip turned blue,
I would've jumped a motorcycle

971
01:54:27,270 --> 01:54:29,310
onto a speeding train.

972
01:54:30,310 --> 01:54:32,060
For you.

973
01:54:33,650 --> 01:54:37,070
But once that strip turned blue...

974
01:54:37,150 --> 01:54:40,530
...I could no longer do
any of those things.

975
01:54:40,610 --> 01:54:43,080
Not anymore.

976
01:54:43,160 --> 01:54:45,540
Because I was gonna be a mother.

977
01:54:48,750 --> 01:54:50,670
Can you understand that?

978
01:54:53,750 --> 01:54:55,420
Yes.

979
01:54:56,420 --> 01:54:58,630
But why didn't you...

980
01:54:58,720 --> 01:55:01,010
...tell me then, instead of now?

981
01:55:02,010 --> 01:55:04,300
Once you knew, you'd claim her.

982
01:55:04,390 --> 01:55:06,350
And I didn't want that.

983
01:55:07,100 --> 01:55:09,310
Not your decision to make.

984
01:55:09,390 --> 01:55:11,440
Yes.

985
01:55:11,520 --> 01:55:14,860
But it's the right decision,
and I made it for my daughter.

986
01:55:15,860 --> 01:55:19,570
She deserved to be born
with a clean slate.

987
01:55:20,570 --> 01:55:22,570
But with you...

988
01:55:22,660 --> 01:55:26,540
...she would've been born
into a world she shouldn't have.

989
01:55:28,250 --> 01:55:30,460
I had to choose.

990
01:55:31,670 --> 01:55:33,670
I chose her.

991
01:55:36,130 --> 01:55:38,920
You know, five years ago,

992
01:55:39,010 --> 01:55:43,840
if I had to make a list of impossible
